#SciSpark's sRDD
##Overview
The purpose of this notebook is to introduce the user to the concept of the scientific Resilient Distributed Dataset (sRDD) that is the core of SciSpark. Topics to be addressed here include ingesting data into the sRDD from netCDF files, operations available for data within the sRDD, and passing the sRDD from the Scala/Java environment to the Python environment. 


The data used in this notebook is the [Tropical Rainfall Measuring Mission (TRMM) 0.25° x 0.25°degree 3-hourly dataset](http://disc.sci.gsfc.nasa.gov/precipitation/documentation/TRMM_README/TRMM_3B42_readme.shtml) acquired from the [GES DIS Mirador site] (http://mirador.gsfc.nasa.gov/). 

###Reference
Palamuttam, Rahul, Renato Marroquín Mogrovejo, Christian Mattmann, Brian Wilson, Kim Whitehall, Rishi Verma, Lewis McGibbney, and Paul Ramirez. "SciSpark: Applying In-memory Distributed Computing to Weather Event Detection and Tracking." ([PDF](http://geo-bigdata.github.io/2015/papers/S08216.pdf))

%md ## The SciSpark Context The ***SciSpark context*** is analogous to the ***sparkcontext***, in that it provides the connection to the Spark cluster. The ***SciSpark context*** extends all the functionalities of a ***sparkcontext*** to create RDDs, create variables and perform computations within the cluster, to operate on common scientific formats.
Most scientific formats are self describing, multidimensional, multivariable, portable, scalable, appendable, sharable, archivable. Common formats include [Network Common Data Form (netCDF)](http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/software/netcdf/) and [Hierarchical Data Format (HDF)](https://www.hdfgroup.org/) which both offer extensive APIs in various languages.
The implementation of the ***SciSpark context*** is a wrapper function around the ***sparkcontext***.

paragraphs.text:
%md ## What is the sRDD The scientific Resilient Distributed Dataset (sRDD), exploits Apache Spark's concept of RDDs for multi-dimensional data representing a scientific measurement that can be subset by time, or by space. The RDD notion directly enables the reuse of array data across multi-stage operations and it ensures data can be replicated, distributed and easily reconstructed in different storage tiers, e.g., memory for fast interactivity, SSDs for near real time, and spinning disk for later operations.
The sRDD supports multidimensional data and processing of scientific algorithms in the MapReduce paradigm within a distributed environment. The core of the sRDD is a self-documented array class called the ***sciTensor*** that allows for scientific formats to be read into an equivalent datatype thus creating the sRDD. ![loading data into sciTensor](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SciSpark/scispark_zeppelin_notebooks/master/images/srdd1.png) Figure 1: Illustration of the sRDD manifestation in memory
SciSpark currently provides methods to create sRDDs that: (1) loads data from network Common Data Form (netCDF) files into the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) in a parallelized manner; (2) preserve the logical representation of structured and dimensional data in via the ***sciTensor*** datatype; and (3) create a partition function that divides the multidimensional array by time (to be expanded to space as well). ***sRDDs*** are cached (in-memory) in the SciSpark engine support data reuse between multi-staged analytics. Each of these methods require their own set of input parameters, usually including a path to the data on HDFS, the variable(s) to be placed in the ***sciTensor***, the number of paritions (chunks to make that will be operated on in parallel) to be used, and/ or a list of the files. Please view the [SciSpark ScalaDocs](https://scispark.jpl.nasa.gov/api/#org.dia.loaders.package) for more on the loader methods available and their usage. The paritioning is currently determined according to the number of files to read data from and the number of paritions to use.
#### Example with real data Let's consider netCDF data from the HDFS into the sRDD. The required parameters for this call are the location of the data on HDFS, the variable(s) in the file to be extracted, and the number of paritions to use.

%md ## The sciTensor The data are loaded into sciTensors (as illustrated in Figure 1). The data are now in the sciTensors datatypes in the distributed memory of the Spark cluster. The sciTensor datatype is a self-documented array that keeps a list of arrays for a variable arrays and maintains associated metadata in a hashmap. Users can query the hashmap via the [SciSpark API](https://scispark.jpl.nasa.gov/api/), perform matrix operations on the arrays, and add data to the sciTensor.
The following components can be accessed within the ***sciTensor***: *.varInUse*: a String representing the current variable the sciTensor is referencing *.variables*: an array representing the actual data associated with the variable *.metaData*: a tuple (String, String) representing any metadata from the original file to be associated with the variable.
Metadata can be added to the ***sciTensor*** using the *insertDictionary* method. This method expects a key-value String pair. ``` sciTensor.insertDictionary(("key","value")) ```
#### Example with real data In this example, we wil add the *Date* as a metadata field to the sciTensors associated with the TRMM data that were read into the sRDD in the previous step. Here the *Date* is determined from parsing the filename. The 3B42 3hrly TRMM filenames typically have the format ***3B42.YYYYMMDD.HH.vv.nc***. To parse the date from this filename the below line is used: ``` val filename = p1.metaData("SOURCE").split("/").last.split("\\.")(1) + p1.metaData("SOURCE").split("/").last.split("\\.")(2) ```

paragraphs.text:
%md
The sciTensors can be further operated on in the parallel enviroment of the sRDD via the typical [Spark Transformations](http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/programming-guide.html#transformations) e.g. map, filter, and mapParitions. The operations that can be performed include: (1) relational operations (for masking data); (2) arithmetic operations; and (3) linear algebra operations. **(1) Relational operators** Relational operators are commonly used to mask data. The end user can determine which variable in the sciTensor (i.e. the data associated with that variable) to perform the operation on. If no variable in the sciTensor is explicitly identified to use in the operation, the operation will occur on the *varInUse* by default. The valid relational operators for sciTensors are given in the table below.
Relational Operator Description
< less than a user-defined value
<= less than or equals to a user-defined value
> greater than than a user-defined value
>= greater than of equals a user-defined value
:=

equals to a user-defined value
!= not equals to a user-defined value

An example of the syntax using the "equals to" operator is given as: ``` val wins = 3.0 val x = sRDD.map(p => p("metaDataOption" := wins) ```
#### Example with real data Our data is TRMM 3hrly rate data. Let's assume we are interested in rates greater than 0.1mm/hr. Then, we can mask out the data accordingly for further calcuations, by implementing the ***>=*** operator, which is used to change the values less than 0.1 to 0.0. Other operators available in SciSpark for masking given in the table below. Note that by masking the data, the values that do not meet the critera are converted to 0.0

paragraphs.text:
%md **(2) Arithmetic operations** Arithmetic operators maybe useful for tasks such as converting units, determining totals within time periods or finding averages. To perform such tasks in SciSpark, the sciTensor is operated on. The end user can determine which variable in the sciTensor (i.e. the data associated with that variable) to perform the operation on. If no variable in the sciTensor is explicitly identified to use in the operation, the operation will occur on the *varInUse* by default. Operators are provided for both in-place operators (i.e. the original sciTensor is changed) and copy operators (i.e. a copy of the sciTensor is created). For scalar operations, the scalar must be represented as a Double. The table of available arithmetic operators are provided in the table below.
Arithmetic Operator Description
+ In-place scalar or matrix element-wise addition.
- In-place scalar or matrix element-wise subtraction.
* In-place scalar or matrix element-wise multiplication.
/ In-place scalar or matrix element-wise division.
:+

Scalar or matrix addition element-wise copy operation.
:- Scalar or matrix element-wise subtraction copy operation.
:* Scalar or matrix element-wise multiplication copy operation.
:/ Scalar or matrix element-wise division copy operation.

An example of the syntax for a copy scalar addition operation is given as: ``` val wins = 3.0 val x = sRDD.map(p => p("metaDataOption" :+ wins) ```
#### Example with real data Let's convert the TRMM 3hrly rate data from a rate to 3hrly accumulations. To do this, we will leverage the in-place scalar multiplication operation.

paragraphs.text:
%md
**(3) Other operations available for sciTensors**
(a) Masking of data within the **sciTensors**
Though similar to leveraging a relational operator to mask data, this operation returns the same AbstractTensor (as opposed to a copy).

```
val filtered = sciT.mask(p => p < value, value_to_mask_to)

```
The mask funtion utilizes a lambda expression, which gives us the ability to do more
complicated tasks like masking a range of temperatures.

```
val filtered = sciT.mask(p => p > lower_value || p < upper_value )

```

It is also possible to set a mask value to be used. 

```
val filtered = sciT.setMask(value_to_mask_to) <= value
```
(b) Reshaping the data array
Sometimes it is necessary to reshape the data i.e. the AbstractTensor, in a operation. For this functionality, **SciSpark** provides the following API:

```
val reshaped = sRDD.map(sciT => sciT("varname").reshape( Array(Int * Int), "reshaped_varname"))
```
Here the data in *varname* is reshaped to the shape given with in the Array of Ints, and a new Abstract Tensor is created and added to the sciTensor with the name "reshaped_varname"

paragraphs.text:
%md ## Maintaining time in the sRDD The sRDD is a distributed dataset. When the data are read into memory, they are collated in groups according to the number of paritions to be used, then actions are performed in parallel on the data in each parition. There is no guarantee that the data in each partition or the sRDD are in any type of order. However, maintaining a timeseries throughout a set of calculations maybe prudent for *some* evaluations. Given the inherent distributed environment, this is not a trivial task. ![maintaining time in the sRDD](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SciSpark/scispark_zeppelin_notebooks/master/images/groupByApproach.png) Figure 2: Illustration of the maintenance of the time sequence in the sRDD
To maintain the timeseries in SciSpark,a metadata field in the ***sciTensor*** representing the datetime can be used. This metadata field **SHOULD** be created by the user when the data is being loaded into the ***sciTensors*** (or at anytime). The datetime is usually available in the filename and can be parsed. For example, above when the data was read into the ***sRDD***, the metaData **Date** was created from the filename. Once the datetime is known, inorder to maintain the timeseries, a copy of the data is generated, and tuples between consecutive datetimes created. For example, for the dates 2016060100, 2016060101, 2016060102, 2016060103, 2016060104, 2016060105, the following linkages will occur: ``` Map(Date -> 2016060100) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060101) Map(Date -> 2016060101) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060102) Map(Date -> 2016060102) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060103) Map(Date -> 2016060103) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060104) Map(Date -> 2016060104) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060105) ``` In this way, time between consecutive frames will always be maintained, and the timeseries. #### Example with real data Let's demonstrate creating the tuples with the TRMM data. We will create the timeseries with the data so as to determine 6hr- and 12hr- accumulations. Note that because this data is 3hrly, we add 3 to the 'Date'.

The sRDD is a distributed dataset. When the data are read into memory, they are collated in groups according to the number of paritions to be used, then actions are performed in parallel on the data in each parition. There is no guarantee that the data in each partition or the sRDD are in any type of order. However, maintaining a timeseries throughout a set of calculations maybe prudent for some evaluations.
Given the inherent distributed environment, this is not a trivial task.

           Figure 2: Illustration of the maintenance of the time sequence in the sRDD


To maintain the timeseries in SciSpark,a metadata field in the sciTensor representing the datetime can be used. This metadata field SHOULD be created by the user when the data is being loaded into the sciTensors (or at anytime). The datetime is usually available in the filename and can be parsed. For example, above when the data was read into the sRDD, the metaData Date was created from the filename.
Once the datetime is known, inorder to maintain the timeseries, a copy of the data is generated, and tuples between consecutive datetimes created. For example, for the dates 2016060100, 2016060101, 2016060102, 2016060103, 2016060104, 2016060105, the following linkages will occur:

Map(Date -> 2016060100) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060101)
Map(Date -> 2016060101) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060102)
Map(Date -> 2016060102) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060103)
Map(Date -> 2016060103) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060104)
Map(Date -> 2016060104) connected to Map(Date -> 2016060105)

In this way, time between consecutive frames will always be maintained, and the timeseries.

Example with real data

Let's demonstrate creating the tuples with the TRMM data. We will create the timeseries with the data so as to determine 6hr- and 12hr- accumulations. Note that because this data is 3hrly, we add 3 to the 'Date'.

paragraphs.text:
val consecTRMM = accu3hrly.flatMap(p => {
    List((p.metaData("Date").toInt, p), (p.metaData("Date").toInt + 3, p)) // 1. Duplicate each scitensor into a List of tuples i.e. List((hour + 3, p), (hour, p))
}).groupBy(_._1)                                                           // 2. Since we flatmapped we obtain an RDD of consisting of tuples (H, P) where H is the hour key. Note that there are two copies of each array mapped to the current time and next time
    .map(p => p._2.map(e => e._2).toList)                                  // 3. The group by operation enables us to create Lists that contain tuples where the hour key is equal.
    .filter(p => p.size > 1)                                               // 4. Since we output different keys initially for the same sciTensor, the resulting pairs of tuples consist of the same key but different sciTensors that correspond to consecutive time periods.
    .map(p => p.sortBy(_.metaData("Date").toInt))                          // 5. The overall transformation : (p*) => ((hour + 3, p*), (hour, p*)) => ((hour, (p+3)*), (hour, p*)) => ((p+3)*, p*)
    .map(p => (p(0), p(1)))

paragraphs.title: Sharing data between Scala/Java and Python
paragraphs.text:
%md
At this point, we may wish to visualize the data *while* it is still in the sRDD leveraging Python's matplotlib. To do this, we need to pass the data from the Scala environment to the Python environment. 

####Passing data
This is done leveraging the Py4J Gateway and the "Object exchange" property in Apache Zeppelin that shares the **sparkcontext** and **SciSparkContext** between environments. We can pass the entire RDD using the "Object exchange" thus reducing the need for I/O inorder to visualize by leveraging the [PySpark MLLIB common library](https://spark.apache.org/docs/1.5.0/api/python/_modules/pyspark/mllib/common.html).  

However, the Py4J environment requires Java objects. Furthermore, Py4J by default passes the objects by reference (as opposed to value) within the JVM. In order to access the actual data in the Python enviroment, the data will have to be passed as an arraybuffer object. 

The sciTensor provides the following methods to access the data stored within. 
* The *.data* method returns a flattened array of doubles of the values associated with the varInUse. 
* The *.shape* method returns the shape of the original data array. 
```
val t = sRDD.map(p => (p("varName").data, p("varName").shape))
```

To convert Scala array to a Java ArrayBuffer object, leverage the java.nio library as demonstrated below:

```
import java.nio

val scalaBytebuffer = java.nio.ByteBuffer.allocate(8*scalaDataArray.length)
bbuf.asDoubleBuffer.put(java.nio.DoubleBuffer.wrap(scalaDataArray))
val javaDataBuffer = bbuf.array
```

In general, to put an object from the Scala/ Java environment use:
```
val myVar = ...
z.put("myVarName", myVar)
```

To get the object from Python use:
```
%pyspark
myVar = z.get("myVarName")
```
The reverse is also true.

####Example with real data
Let's pass the 12hrly accumulation data to the Python environment.

result.msg:
At this point, we may wish to visualize the data while it is still in the sRDD leveraging Python's matplotlib. To do this, we need to pass the data from the Scala environment to the Python environment.

Passing data

This is done leveraging the Py4J Gateway and the “Object exchange” property in Apache Zeppelin that shares the sparkcontext and SciSparkContext between environments. We can pass the entire RDD using the “Object exchange” thus reducing the need for I/O inorder to visualize by leveraging the PySpark MLLIB common library.

However, the Py4J environment requires Java objects. Furthermore, Py4J by default passes the objects by reference (as opposed to value) within the JVM. In order to access the actual data in the Python enviroment, the data will have to be passed as an arraybuffer object.

The sciTensor provides the following methods to access the data stored within.

  • The .data method returns a flattened array of doubles of the values associated with the varInUse.
  • The .shape method returns the shape of the original data array.
    val t = sRDD.map(p => (p("varName").data, p("varName").shape))

To convert Scala array to a Java ArrayBuffer object, leverage the java.nio library as demonstrated below:

import java.nio

val scalaBytebuffer = java.nio.ByteBuffer.allocate(8*scalaDataArray.length)
bbuf.asDoubleBuffer.put(java.nio.DoubleBuffer.wrap(scalaDataArray))
val javaDataBuffer = bbuf.array

In general, to put an object from the Scala/ Java environment use:

val myVar = ...
z.put("myVarName", myVar)

To get the object from Python use:

%pyspark
myVar = z.get("myVarName")

The reverse is also true.

Example with real data

Let's pass the 12hrly accumulation data to the Python environment.

paragraphs.title: On the scala/java side to send the data:
paragraphs.text:
import java.nio

val sliding6hrlyArrays = sliding6hrly.map(p => {
    val listData = new java.util.ArrayList[Any]()
    val scalaBytebuffer = java.nio.ByteBuffer.allocate(8*p("pcp").data.length)
    scalaBytebuffer.asDoubleBuffer.put(java.nio.DoubleBuffer.wrap(p("pcp").data))
    listData.add(scalaBytebuffer.array)
    listData.add(p("pcp").shape)
    listData.add(java.lang.Integer.valueOf(p.metaData("Date").toInt))
    listData //listData is a Java List containing a Java arrayBuffer and a Scala array
})
z.put("sliding6hrlyList", sliding6hrlyArrays)

paragraphs.title: On the Python side to access the data:
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from pyspark.mllib.common import _java2py
import numpy

sliding6hrlyPy = z.get("sliding6hrlyList")

pythonRDD = _java2py(sc, sliding6hrlyPy)

def convert_to_numpy(aList):
    '''
        aList is  [javaDataBuffer, p("pcp").shape, dtime] in the sRDD
    '''
    dt = numpy.dtype('d')
    dt = dt.newbyteorder('>')
    da = numpy.frombuffer(aList[0], dtype=dt)
    da.shape = (aList[1][0], aList[1][1])
    return (da, aList[2])
    
listOfNumpy = pythonRDD.map(lambda t: convert_to_numpy(t))
collectedListOfNumpy = listOfNumpy.collect()

print len(collectedListOfNumpy), sorted(collectedListOfNumpy, key=lambda x:x[1])[0], collectedListOfNumpy[0][0].shape

paragraphs.title: Visualize the results with matplotlib
paragraphs.text: %pyspark def make_imgs(currData): import numpy as np import glob, os import subprocess import matplotlib matplotlib.use('Agg') os.system("export DISPLAY=:0") import matplotlib.pyplot as plt plt.rcdefaults() import cStringIO import base64 from mpl_toolkits.basemap import Basemap, cm lat1s = np.arange(-50,50,.25) lon1s = np.arange(-180,180,.25) lon1, lat1 = np.meshgrid(lon1s, lat1s) mp = Basemap(projection = 'merc', llcrnrlon = min(lon1s), urcrnrlon = max(lon1s), llcrnrlat = min(lat1s), urcrnrlat = max(lat1s), resolution = 'l') x1, y1 = mp(lon1, lat1) clevs1 = [0,1,2.5,5,7.5,10,15,20,30,40,50,70,100,150,200,250,300,400,500,600,750] cs1 = mp.contourf(x1, y1, currData[0], clevs1, cmap=cm.s3pcpn) # Add Grid Lines mp.drawparallels(np.arange(-50., 50., 10.), labels=[1,0,0,0], fontsize=8) mp.drawmeridians(np.arange(-180., 181., 20.), labels=[0,0,0,1], fontsize=8) mp.drawcoastlines(linewidth = 0.25) mp.drawcountries(linewidth = 0.25) # Add Colorbar cbar1 = mp.colorbar(cs1, location='bottom', pad="30%") cbar1.set_label("pcp total in mm") # Add Title plt.title('6-hr total starting at '+str(currData[1])) img1 = cStringIO.StringIO() plt.savefig(img1, format='png') imgStr = "data:image/png;base64," imgStr += base64.b64encode(img1.getvalue().strip()) plt.close() return (currData[1],imgStr) arrayOfImgArray = listOfNumpy.map(lambda t: make_imgs(t)).collect() sorted(arrayOfImgArray, key=lambda x: x[0]) vizStr = "%html " for imgArray in arrayOfImgArray: vizStr += "" print imgArray[0] print vizStr
